In <HEBRAIS.94Jul26194926@saguenay.IRO.UMontreal.CA>, hebrais@saguenay.IRO.UMontreal.CA (Philippe Hebrais) writes:
>In article <JYL.94Jul23155902@burgess.eng.sun.com> jyl@burgess.eng.sun.com (Jacob Levy) writes:
>
>> What I'm after is not just establishing a secure
>> channel with a second party but at the same time establishing the identity
>> of the second party without having to trust anyone else. Is this possible
>> at all?
>
[...]
>ZK proofs are a way to convince someone that you know a solution to a
>problem without revealing anything about your (or any other) solution
>to that problem.  If somehow, you pick a problem in such a way that
>only you know the solution, anyone can recognize you by the fact you
>can solve that problem.  In other words, to prove you are yourself,
>you engage in a ZK protocol that will convince your friend you know
>the solution to that problem you picked.

For example (I think), your friend encrypts a message using your public key
and you return the same message encrypted with your friend's public key...
